  "text": "Once upon a matchday — it was the third-place play-off, on the 18th of July 2026 — two teams walked out under the soft evening lights. A ten-goal bronze-medal classic ended with England on top — and a scoring record for Kylian Mbappé. Officially a match for third place; unofficially, one of the maddest games the tournament produced.\n\nFirst, in the 3rd minute, Declan Rice made it 0–1; then, in the 18th minute, Ezri Konsa made it 0–2; then, in the 38th minute, Bukayo Saka made it 0–3; then, in the 46th minute, Bukayo Saka made it 0–4; then, in the 48th minute, Kylian Mbappé made it 1–4; then, in the 54th minute, Bradley Barcola made it 2–4; then, in the 66th minute, Kylian Mbappé made it 3–4; then, in the 87th minute, Bukayo Saka made it 3–5; then, in the 96th minute, Ousmane Dembélé made it 4–5; and at last, in the 98th minute, Jude Bellingham made it 4–6.\n\nEngland raced into a four-goal lead through Declan Rice, Ezri Konsa and a Bukayo Saka double, and it looked like a rout. France roared back: Kylian Mbappé struck twice around a Bradley Barcola goal to close it to 3-4 and set nerves jangling. But Saka completed his hat-trick from the penalty spot, Ousmane Dembélé kept France alive, and Jude Bellingham had the very last word. Mbappé's double moved him above Lionel Messi as the World Cup's all-time leading scorer — yet it was England who went home with the bronze.\n\nAnd so the story ended France 4–6 England. England carried on their long journey, and France lay down to rest. Every goal in this tale is a true one — kept safe and provable on the blockchain by TxLINE — so you can close your eyes knowing not a single fact was ever made up. Sleep well, and goodnight.",
